      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0228f6d18dfb6143",
        "text": "If we now take seriously the threat to thought posed by its reduction to identity, we must of course also question the supposedly universalist alternative that the liberal critics of identity have on offer. With Rorty, we fall back on the replacement of abstract humanism by something \"place-bound and eth- no-centric,\" hence that corpus of shared conventions dependent on \"national pride\" that determines the meaning of the word \"we.\" For Lepore, too, liberalism is saved by \"a plea for the nation,\" and for Lilla there is \"no liberal politics without a sense of we.\" For Lilla, the only answer to populist demagoguery on the one hand and postmodern identity on the other is to take refuge in \"something we all share as Americans, but which has nothing to do with our identities.\" With their undermining of the \"universal democratic we on which solidarity can be grounded,\" Lilla laments, progressives have \"abolished rather than created citizenship.\" \"We is where it all begins.\"\n\nThis is the core idea of the liberal alternative to identity, but it is also the greatest liberal burden. Once the truth that bound humanity has been discarded, there is no longer a clear boundary between we-liberalism and identity politics. Once one rejects the abstract concept of humanity, Kant would have agreed with the critics of liberalism, the post-metaphysical reincarnation of a unionist politics is itself just a form of identity politics: not by black people, LGBf() advocates, feminists, or members of other minorities, but by all those who feel comfortable starting a political debate with the phrase \"we Americans,\" \"we Germans,\" \"we Israelis.\"\nFor true universalists, however, \"we\" should never be the beginning of politics; it can only be its never-final outcome. For politics, the most important debate - and sometimes war - revolves around who is included in this \"we,\" of which the American Civil War is the most obvious example. "
